<% content_for :title, "Modal + form swap — erbswap" %>

<h2>Example 1 — Modal + form swap</h2>

<p class="example-intro">
  Click the button below. A modal opens and its body is freshly fetched
  (<strong>Pattern B</strong>: opener-driven swap, so the next open is always a
  clean state &mdash; no reset gymnastics). Each task-button is a form whose
  response replaces the frame inline (<strong>Pattern A</strong>: form-driven swap).
</p>

<button type="button"
        class="button"
        data-erbswap-action="load"
        data-erbswap-src="<%= examples_tasks_modal_body_path %>"
        data-erbswap-target="task-frame"
        data-erbswap-swap="replace"
        data-modal-open="task-modal">
  Open Task Modal
</button>

<dialog id="task-modal" class="modal">
  <div class="modal__content">
    <%= render "tasks/modal_initial", tasks: TasksController::TASKS %>

    <form method="dialog" class="modal__close-form">
      <button type="submit" class="button button--ghost">Close</button>
    </form>
  </div>
</dialog>

<details class="example-source">
  <summary>What's happening?</summary>
  <ol>
    <li>Click the button. A small bit of demo glue calls <code>dialog.showModal()</code>, and <strong>erbswap</strong> fires a fetch to <code><%= examples_tasks_modal_body_path %></code>.</li>
    <li>The server renders <code>_modal_initial.html.erb</code> as plain HTML &mdash; no JSON, no envelope, just an ERB partial.</li>
    <li><strong>erbswap</strong> replaces <code>#task-frame</code> via <code>outerHTML</code> with the response.</li>
    <li>Each task-button is a form with <code>data-erbswap-form="true"</code>. Submitting it swaps <code>#task-frame</code> with the success / empty / error partial.</li>
    <li>Every state's partial wraps in <code>&lt;div id="task-frame"&gt;</code>. That's <strong>Invariant #1</strong>: same frame id across every state.</li>
  </ol>
</details>
